A recruiter asks you what you made at your last job or wants to know what you want to make in this job.

What should you do? I’ll give you some scripts at the end.

Before you go to a job interview you can use websites like Glassdoor or Salary.com to get an idea of a comp range. But remember, this information is not always accurate because its based on what people report, and not all people are honest. Companies like Glassdoor or Salary.com are not auditing the information to determine if it’s true. 

When you speak to the recruiter say this:

 “Thanks for asking me, but I'd like to know the salary range the company has in mind for this role.” 

If the recruiter keeps asking then say this:

“I'm looking for fair compensation that is based on my skills and experience. Can you tell me what a typical offer would look like?”

Or say this:

“I’m looking for my next career move as a long-term investment, and I believe in fair compensation based on market value as a whole including benefits. Can you give me an example of what a typical offer would look like, including all aspects such as base salary, bonus, benefits.”

NOTE: In many states its illegal for companies to ask you how much you make.

#whatareyoursalaryexpectations #jobinterview #salary #salarynegotiation

Here’s the difference between LinkedIn and a resume, why using both will give you the best chance of job search success, and I’ll give you tips you can implement at the end of the video.

A resume is used for targeted hits and LinkedIn is used to tell people your career journey.

Your LinkedIn gives a complete picture of who you are as a professional, what you've done, and what you've achieved. It’s where recruiters and hiring managers go to find candidates like you AND it’s a great place to add as many relevant keywords that a recruiter would be searching for to find you.

Your resume is a snapshot, a precise picture of your most relevant experiences tailored to the job you're targeting, and it’s what you should use to apply for jobs.

Your resume should be laser-focused by incorporating keywords from the job description of the job you are applying for.

Upload your resume to your LinkedIn page because now LinkedIn can search through resumes, so recruiters can find you more easily and it can save you time because if a recruiter finds you they don’t have to wait to present your resume to a hiring manager.

Add the link to your LinkedIn profile so when you apply for jobs so that recruiters and hiring managers can learn more about you as a professional.

Use AI to help you prepare for your interview

There are 4 areas of focus before you go into an interview and in this video I’ll cover company research.

You need to learn as much as you can about the company, its products or services, its culture, and its goals. ChatGPT’s data only goes to September 2021, so we have to feed it information. 

First, go to https://chat.openai.com/

Type in the following prompt:

“Analyze the mission page of [company name] and provide a detailed examination of the following aspects: Core Values, Mission Statement, Goals and Objectives, Stakeholder Engagement, Impact and Sustainability, Evolution and Future Outlook. Please provide a comprehensive analysis of each aspect, supported by relevant examples and quotations from the mission page where applicable.”

Then, go to the company’s mission page on their website. Copy the text from the page. Then go to ChatGPT, paste the information. Then hit enter.

Next, type in the following prompt:

“Please analyze the latest news articles or press releases about [company name] and provide a comprehensive analysis of the following aspects: Major Announcements, Industry Impact, Corporate Strategy, Future Outlook.”

Then, find recent press releases or news articles.. Copy the text. Then go to ChatGPT, paste the information. Then hit enter.

Lastly type in the following prompt.

“Based on this thread, create 10 interview questions a candidate can ask a hiring manager who is interviewing for the following role” 

Then go to the job descriptoin of the job you’re interviewing for, copy it, then go back to ChatGPT, paste the job description. Then hit enter and watch AI do it’s magic

Red flag questions to watch out for when you're in a job interview

Questions are hints at what you should expect in a job, so pay attention to what you are being asked. 

“How do you handle difficult people?

This question sounds like there’s a bully on the team. 

Or someone you are going to report to is going to be difficult to work with. 

The company either can’t fire them because they’re a top performer OR they’re going firing them. 

“How do you handle miscommunication?”

There are communication issues either on the team you’d be working with or in the organization.

“How do you handle ambiguity?”

You’re going to have a manager who doesn’t communicate which will hurt your career. 

Because they will have unclear expectations of you because aren’t clear communicators.

Lies you can say in a job interview.

When an interviewer asks you about your future plans, they want to know two things:
* How long you plan to stay with the company.
* Whether your career goals align with the potential role.
Even if you don’t plan on staying long you can’t say that in an interview. 

Be honest about your personal career goals and explain how the job fits into your career path.

Here's an example of what how you can respond.

"In five years, I see myself as an expert in this field and a valuable member of the team. This role aligns with my future goals because..." then talk about your future goals and then say

"I'm excited about [specific aspect of the job/field] and the ability to deepen my expertise."

How to profesionally lie: why you’re leaving

Lies you can say in a job interview.

If you're asked why you're leaving your current job during an interview, you don't need to tell them why.

Interviewers are looking for red flags when they ask this question. Even if you are leaving because your boss or work environment are toxic, don't talk about it because talking about it can make you look bad. 

Instead highlight the good parts of your present job. Focus on how the new job you're interviewing for fits with your needs and goals..

Here’s how you can respond, "I'm looking for a new challenge where I can apply my skills in [talk about your skillset] and where I can learn more about [talk about what the company is working on and anything you've read about in the news], which I know your company excels in. For example [then give a relevant example].”

If you’re asked about a gap in your resume. Just tell them you signed an NDA. 

Kidding!

Here’s what you can do instead. 

First you need to realize that you don’t have to worry about the gap on your resume, because that resume got you an interview. 

Whatever is written on your resume, got you in front of the interviewer.

Here’s how you talk it and it’s super easy. 

If you had a gap because you went back to school, got training, volunteered ,or took a leave of absence to learn to enrich your knowledge then talk about it. 

If you were laid off, tell them it’s because the company had mass layoffs. I’ve been laid off three times and yes companies understand that it’s not your fault. 

For anything else, tell them it was for personal reasons. In the US, employers can’t ask about your marital or family status and honestly it’s none of their business.

Here’s how to answer the job interview question “Do you have any questions?” by using a technique I like to call the ‘Ask-Back’

Yes, I know what that sounded like. I’m working on my retention.

Now just for some background, I’m an active recruiter who worked at Google, Lyft, Uber & TikTok and every time a candidate asked me this during my interview they almost always got a job offer.

The 'Ask-Back' works like this. When an interviewer asks 'Do you have any questions for us?', 

Don't just say 'No'. That seems like you don't care. 

And don't ask about things like vacation time or benefits - save that question for the recruiter

Instead, ask, "Did I answer all your questions? Is there anything you want me to explain in more depth?” This shows you want people to understand you, which shows that you are a good communicator.

After that then you can ask questions about the job, the company, and the team. I have videos what else you can ask in my Interview playlist because sometimes people want to know

Day 4: September’s Surge To Success, Overcoming Anxiety

Here are steps you can take to help:

1 - Unburden Yourself: 

Every time you finish an interview, mentally tell yourself, “Next!" Keep the forward momentum because something even better may be around the corner.

2 - Keep Perspective: 

It's important to understand that while jobs can be game-changers, it's not the end of the world if one of them doesn't pan out.

3 - Stay Confident: If you’re overly anxious, you won’t put your best foot forward. Instead, be present during the experience of the interview. 

It’s a chance to learn and grow.

4 - Embrace the Process: 

Instead of dreading interviews, enjoy them! 

When you walk in with a genuine "take it or leave it" attitude, it radiates confidence. 

Enjoy meeting the interviewer. 

Interviews are an incredible way to network so after your interview, 

be sure to add your interviewer to your LinkedIn network. 

That way even if the interview doesn’t work out, 

in the future that person may work at a company you may want to work at,
 and you can reach out to them for a referral.

When you shift your focus from desperately needing the job, to enjoying the process, you'll naturally perform better.

Every interview is a learning experience and an opportunity for advancement.
.
.

Here’s the exact method I teach my clients to help them prep for interviews

Using the Four Pillars of Interview Prep Technique.

And if you’re wondering who I am to be telling you this, I’ve coached hundreds of professionals, helping them land their dream jobs

General Questions:
These are questions you’ll be asked in every interview.

Like, Tell Me About Yourself? or Why are you interested in this position?

The Company:
Research the company.

Are there any products or projects they’re working on that you find interesting?
What do you like about them?

Technical Questions:
Use the job description to identify the core skills & the types of questions they’ll ask.

Use the STAR method to answer and

Have stories from your experience & talk about your skills in action.

Use exact figures, dates, and outcomes.

Questions for Them:
This is the most important one.

Ask about their challenges, the role, and ask your interviewer about their journey in the company. #jobinterview #jobinterviewtips #jobinterviewquestions

Friendly reminder during the holidays. People will pressure you into talking about & doing things because they mean well, but it may not be your journey. 

Hold to your boundaries. People with strong opinions are very rarely convinced of an opposing view. If your goal is to get through to him/her and align them with your views, it is unlikely to happen.

Tip when setting boundaries. Tell them your point of view and end with the consequence.

For example, if someone gives you unsolicited parenting advice say:

"I appreciate your experience, but I'm confident in my parenting choices."

Or if someone asks you overly personal questions:

"That's a personal topic, and I'm not comfortable discussing it right now." and you can follow it with "I'd rather talk about something else."

#boundaries #stevejobsquote

Take your PTO.

When my direct reports would ask me permission to take PTO I’d immediately correct them and tell them to say “Hey Farah, I’m taking PTO from this date to this date.” 

I’d ask them if they had someone to cover for them while they were away & if they didn’t then I’d help them. 

As someone who’s had their fair share of toxic bosses I know how important taking PTO is for physical & mental health. 

You are the most important person in your world. 

Take your PTO.
